 18  /-- The set of upper bounds of a set. -/
 19  def upper_bounds (s : set α) : set α := { x | ∀ ⦃a⦄, a ∈ s →  a ≤ x }
id                         └─┘ ┴    └─┘ ┴    ┴ ┴      ┴   ┴ ┴ ┴    ┴ ┴ ┴

 20  /-- The set of lower bounds of a set. -/
 21  def lower_bounds (s : set α) : set α := { x | ∀ ⦃a⦄, a ∈ s → x ≤ a }
id                         └─┘ ┴    └─┘ ┴    ┴ ┴      ┴   ┴ ┴ ┴   ┴ ┴ ┴
src                        └─┘      └─┘      ┴              ┴       ┴

 22  /-- `a` is a least element of a set `s`; for a partial order, it is unique if exists. -/
 23  def is_least (s : set α) (a : α) : Prop := a ∈ s ∧ a ∈ lower_bounds s
id                     └─┘ ┴       ┴            ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ └──────────┘ ┴
src                    └─┘                        ┴   ┴   ┴ └──────────┘
typ                    └─┘ ┴       ┴            ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ └──────────┘ ┴
doc                                                         └──────────┘
 24  /-- `a` is a greatest element of a set `s`; for a partial order, it is unique if exists -/
 25  def is_greatest (s : set α) (a : α) : Prop := a ∈ s ∧ a ∈ upper_bounds s
id                        └─┘ ┴       ┴            ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ └──────────┘ ┴
src                       └─┘                        ┴   ┴   ┴ └──────────┘
typ                       └─┘ ┴       ┴            ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ ┴ └──────────┘ ┴
doc                                                            └──────────┘
 26  /-- `a` is a least upper bound of a set `s`; for a partial order, it is unique if exists. -/
 27  def is_lub (s : set α) : α → Prop := is_least (upper_bounds s)

 28  /-- `a` is a greatest lower bound of a set `s`; for a partial order, it is unique if exists. -/

232  /-Introduction rules for boundedness above and below.
233  Most of the time, it is more efficient to use ⟨w, P⟩ where P is a proof
234  that all elements of the set are bounded by w. However, they are sometimes handy.-/
235  lemma bdd_above.mk (a : α) (H : a ∈ upper_bounds s) : bdd_above s := ⟨a, H⟩

339  /-When there is a min (i.e., in the class semilattice_inf), then the union of
340  two sets which are bounded from below is bounded from below, by the minimum of
341  the bounds for the two sets. With this, we deduce that finite sets are
342  bounded below by induction, and that a finite union of sets which are bounded below
343  is still bounded below.-/
344
